Author: COWAN
Vol / Page: 2/6
Edition:
Quote: This niu was the central symbol of worship under Te Ua's dispensation. The term was the olden Maori word  for the short sticks used by the tohunga in his mystic arts of divination, particularly before a battle. Te Ua's niu was a tall pole or flag-mast, round which the faithful were to march in procession chanting their hymns. <i>Ibid..</i> 157 A tall niu, the pole of worship, stood in the principal part of the settlement; ... There were similar niu masts at other villages ...
